ook is a provocative examination of how present-day Muslims encounter and engage the Divine that offers a different perspective on the Islamic Revival. Dreams That Matter opens up new spaces for an anthropology of the imagination, inviting us to rethink both the imagined and the real.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDream interpretationzEgypt. 0aDreamsxReligious aspectsxIslamvCase studies. 0aDreamszEgypt. 0aEthnopsychologyzEgypt. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aanthropologists.  aanthropology.  acairo.  acontemporary egypt.  acontemporary history.  acultural history.  adivination.  adivine connection.  adivine dreams.  adream diaries.  adream interpretation.  adream interpreters.  adream theory.  aegypt.  aethnography.  afreud.  ahistorians.  aimagination.  aislamic revival.  aislamic tradition.  amaterial life.  amiddle east studies.  amuslims.  anonfiction.  asocial historians.  asocial history.  asocial reform.  asocial science.  asufi group.  asuperstition.  awestern theorists.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025850140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094785640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520947856423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520947856/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY